Hi @rhauch , I am very sorry for continuous delayed replies. Was (and am still) swamped with the new release.

I have discussed with @ymatsuda several times about adding the customizable partition inside the KStream layer, and here is a brief summary of it:
1. The cons of relying on the producer's partitioner are that you need to switch on the topic name if different partitioning scheme are needed for different topics; also one may need to switch on all possible topics in her customized partitioner.
2. The cons of using another partitioner inside KStream along side with Kafka produer's partitioner are that it adds another layer of partitioning on top of it and hence may confuse some users, and also is more vulnerable to resulted different partitioning schemes for shared topics from different processing topics.

Although producer's partitioner cannot completely solve the problem of centralizing partitioning schemes cluster-wise, it is actually a good step towards that: people can use a partition registry service just as the data ser-de schema registry service inside a cluster to manage partitioning schemes, while having the KStream partitioner that relying on the K/V types but not the topic names tends to be more tricky to manage hence they can be scattered across multiple processing jobs.

As for the second point of the cons of a producer's partitioner, users can actually avoid switching on all topics by embedding the default partitioner for the default case as:

```
if (record.partition() != null) {
    // ... sanity check and return the partition.
}

if (topic.equals"topic1") {
    // ... customized partitioning logic 1
} else if (topic.equals"topic2") {
    // ... customized partitioning logic 1
} else {
    return defaultPartitioner.partition(record)
}
```

Hence be comparing these trade-offs, I feel it would be better in the long term to enforce users to a centralized producer's level partitioner. Please do let me know if you see some scenarios that I did not consider enough here.

Again, sorry for the late response on this PR.

@guozhangwang Ping for review. A couple notes:
1. I've updated the list groups api to return GROUP_LOAD_IN_PROGRESS if there are any loading partitions. The AdminClient currently treats this as any other error, but we could allow it to return a flag in addition to the list of groups to indicate whether the list is complete.
2. I did a little refactoring of the group storage callback to ensure that the state transition to Stable only occurs with a valid assignment. I realized that we also needed to verify that we were still in the AwaitingSync state when the callback gets invoked because another member may have tried to join while we were still waiting.
